 and scientific practices. Tracing the political and scientific eradication campaigns, Joshua Buhs's bracing study uses the saga as a means to consider twentieth-century American concepts of nature and environmental stewardship. In telling the story, Buhs explores how human concepts of nature evolve and how these ideas affect the natural and social worlds. Spotlighting a particular issue to discuss larger questions of science, public perceptions, and public policy—from pre-environmental awareness to the activist years of the early environmental movement—The Fire Ant Wars will appeal to historians of science, environmentalists, and biologists alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aTechnology & Engineering / General.2bisacsh  afire ants, invasive species, nature, science, public policy, biology, ecology, south america, mobile, alabama, crops, agriculture, game animals, harvesting, wildlife, cattle, protest, environment, environmentalism, rachel carson, eo wilson, eradication, stewardship, activism, control, nonfiction, habitat, social movements, environmental advocacy, entomology, technology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022607981340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226079844423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226079844/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles